{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and potential drawbacks of reducing tillage on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented benefits of reducing tillage on European farmland include positive effects on earthworms, such as increased biomass, species richness, and abundance (126). It can lead to a greater abundance of some invertebrates (126), an increase in certain weed species (126), and more invertebrate bird food resources in no-till systems (126). For birds, benefits can include higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying dates, and shorter foraging distances (126). Some studies also found a greater abundance of birds like the Eurasian skylark, seed-eating songbirds, and gamebirds in late winter (126), as well as higher species richness or diversity for some bird groups in certain areas (211). Additionally, some bird species may be found at higher densities (211), and there is evidence for higher productivity, nesting success, or earlier laying on reduced tillage fields (211).\n\nPotential drawbacks or inconclusive findings show that reducing tillage can have negative, no, or inconsistent effects on the abundance, biomass, or species richness of some invertebrates and earthworms (126). It may also negatively affect or have no consistent impact on the number of different plant species, some weed species, and mammal abundance (126). In one study, bird preferences for conservation tillage fields decreased over time (126), and another found that crop type influenced the number of weeds under different tillage regimes (126). Some studies found that measures of bird diversity were lower or no different on reduced-tillage fields (211), and that some or all bird species were found at similar or lower densities (211).",
  "action_ids": [
    "126",
    "211"
  ]
}

