{
  "action_id": "24",
  "action_title": "Introduce agri-environment schemes to benefit wild bees",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nFour replicated trials in Europe have shown enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land managed under various European agri-environment schemes, relative to conventionally-managed fields or field margins. These schemes were the Swiss Ecological Compensation Areas (one replicated trial), the German organic arable farming option (one replicated trial), the Dutch botanical and meadow bird agreements (one replicated trial, very low numbers of bee species) and the Scottish Rural Stewardship Scheme (one replicated trial, also included nest-searching queen bumblebees).\nFour replicated trials in Europe found that the number of bees and/or bee species is not enhanced on land managed under agri-environment schemes, including meadow bird agreements in wet grassland in the Netherlands, measures to protect steppe-living birds and compensation measures around a National Park in Spain, and 6 m wide grass field margin strips in England (one replicated trial for each).\nOn a wider landscape scale, two replicated trials in the UK have found bumblebee populations were not enhanced on farmland managed under agri-environment schemes. One trial compared the reproductive success of colonies of the buff-tailed bumblebee Bombus terrestris, the other compared queen bumblebee numbers in spring in conventionally managed field margins, on farms with and without agri-environment schemes."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query":"What are the overall effects of broad-scale agri-environment schemes on farmland biodiversity in Europe?","summary":"A review of agri-environment schemes in Europe found that two out of three schemes were beneficial to wildlife (700). For birds, twenty-four of twenty-six European studies indicated that some or all bird populations or densities increased on sites with agri-environment schemes (700), and twenty-two of twenty-five European studies found that at least some bird species had higher densities or more positive population trends on sites with these schemes (172). However, another fifteen European studies found that some or all bird species showed no increase in density or had similar or lower population levels on such sites (172). Specifically, three UK reviews noted population increases for cirl buntings, corncrakes, and Eurasian thick-knees due to specially-designed schemes, although many other species continued to decline (172).

Regarding plants, seven of eleven European studies revealed that agri-environment schemes either maintained or had little to no effect on plant diversity or species richness (700). Three studies reported an increase in plant species richness in areas with these schemes, while two studies noted a decrease (700). In terms of invertebrates, six of ten European studies demonstrated that agri-environment schemes maintained or had minimal to no effect on the diversity, abundance, or species richness of some invertebrates (700), whereas five studies observed an increase in the abundance or species richness of some invertebrates (700). For wild bees specifically, four replicated European trials showed enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land under agri-environment schemes (24), while another four replicated European trials found no enhancement in the number of bees or bee species (24). Furthermore, two UK trials indicated that bumblebee populations were not enhanced at a landscape scale on farmland with agri-environment schemes (24).

For mammals in the UK, one of four studies found positive effects from agri-environment schemes, while three studies reported mixed results for different regions or species (700).","action_ids":["700","172","24"]}

